 interpreted to bestow these women with family, informational, and reproductive privacy rights. Bridges seeks to turn popular thinking on its head: Poor mothers' lack of privacy is not a function of their reliance on government assistance-rather it is a function of their not bearing any privacy rights in the first place. Until we disrupt the cultural narratives that equate poverty with immorality, poor mothers will continue to be denied this right.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 15. Sep 2020) 0aLow-income mothersxCivil rightsxUnited States. 0aLow-income mothersxCivil rightszUnited States. 0aLow-income mothersxLegal status, laws, etcxUnited States. 0aLow-income mothersxLegal status, laws, etczUnited States. 0aLow-income mothersxLegal status, laws, etc.zUnited States. 0aPoor familiesxLegal status, laws, etc.zUnited States. 0aPovertyxMoral and ethical aspectsxUnited StatesxUnited States. 0aPovertyxMoral and ethical aspectszUnited StateszUnited States. 0aPovertyxMoral and ethical aspectszUnited States. 0aPrivacy, Right ofxUnited States. 0aPrivacy, Right ofzUnited States. 0aPublic welfarexLaw and legislationxMoral and ethical aspectszUnited States. 4aMedicaid. 4aTANF. 4achild protective services. 4afoster care. 4ainformational privacy. 4amoral construction of poverty. 4aprivacy. 4apublic benefits. 4areproductive rights. 4awelfare. 7aLAW / Privacy.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Complete eBook-Package 2017z978311070369640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978150360230440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781503602304423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781503602304.jpg  a978-3-11-070369-6  SUP Complete eBook-Package 2017b2017  aGBV-deGruyter-alles